l barbiere di Siviglia, Cenerentola, La gazza ladra, Matilde di Shabran, and Il viaggio a Reims) as responses, each in its own way, to the history that the composer experienced. Roberts shows that Rossini made probing commentaries on politics and religion in a time of reaction and revolution, and that the composer was well-informed on post-Napoleonic politics. Rossini's comic writing served very serious purposes, exposing the problems and complications of an age that he observed with striking clarity. Warren Roberts is Professor Emeritusof History at the University at Albany, SUNY, and has published extensively on eighteenth-century French culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMusicxPolitical aspectsxHistoryy19th centuryzEurope. 4aModern History. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  a1830 Revolution.  aEuropean history.  aNapoleonic domination.  aPost-Napoleonic Europe.  aRossini.  acultural insights.  ahistory commentary.  amusic commentary.  amusic theory.  amusical development.  aoperas.  apolitical commentary.  apolitics.  areligion.  asatire.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311143132140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782046363?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782046363423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782046363/original  a978-3-11-143132-1  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles